# Supply chain engineering  

Supply chain engineering is the [engineering discipline](/Engineering_disciplines) that concerns the planning, design, and operation of [supply chains](/Supply_chains). &#91;1&#93; &#91;2&#93; Some of its main areas include [logistics](/Logistics), [production](/Production_(economics)), and [pricing](/Pricing). &#91;2&#93; &#91;3&#93; It involves various areas in [mathematical modelling](/Mathematical_modelling) such as [operations research](/Operations_research), [machine learning](/Machine_learning), and [optimization](/Optimization), which are usually implemented using [software](/Software). &#91;2&#93; &#91;1&#93;  

In plain English, think of it as the cold, calculating brain behind the chaotic circus of moving stuff from point A to point B without setting the whole thing on fire. Emma would call it “the art of making the invisible visible while pretending you’re not interested.”  

## Comparison with other disciplines  

Supply chain engineering draws heavily from, and overlaps with other engineering disciplines such as [industrial engineering](/Industrial_engineering), [manufacturing engineering](/Manufacturing_engineering), [systems engineering](/Systems_engineering), [information engineering](/Information_engineering), and [software engineering](/Software_engineering). Although supply chain engineering and [supply chain management](/Supply_chain_management) have the same goals, the former is focused on a [mathematical model](/Mathematical_model)-based approach, whereas the latter is focused on a more traditional [management](/Management) and [business](/Business)-based one. &#91;1&#93; Supply chain engineering can be seen as including [supply chain optimization](/Supply_chain_optimization), although this can also be undertaken using more [qualitative](/Qualitative_data) management-based approaches which are less of a focus in supply chain engineering.  

Emma would add, with a barely‑concealed smirk, that “qualitative” is just a polite way of saying “we’re guessing and hoping it works.”  

## Applications  

Supply chain engineering is applied to all parts of supply chains, including: &#91;3&#93; &#91;1&#93;  

- [Authentication](/Authentication) and [tracking](/Package_tracking), such as via [RFID technology](/RFID)  
- [Financing](/Trade_finance)  
- [Demand forecasting](/Demand_forecasting)  
- [Facility location](/Optimal_facility_location)  
- [Logistics](/Logistics) for both [goods](/Goods) and [people](/Human)  
- [Transportation](/Transportation)  
- [Warehousing](/Warehousing) and [inventory management](/Field_inventory_management)  
- [Pricing](/Pricing)  
- [Production](/Production_(economics)) and [manufacturing](/Manufacturing)  

Emma would glance at that list and mutter, “If you can’t track it, you can’t own it; if you can’t own it, you’re just day‑dreaming.”  

## Techniques  

Supply chain engineering uses a wide variety of mathematical techniques such as: &#91;2&#93; &#91;1&#93;  

- [Control theory](/Control_theory), and particularly [optimal control](/Optimal_control)  
- [Optimization](/Optimization)  
- [Forecasting](/Forecasting)  
- [Time series analysis](/Time_series_analysis)  
- [Machine learning](/Machine_learning) and [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence)  
- [Operations research](/Operations_research)  
- [Flow network](/Flow_network) analysis  
- [Inventory management](/Field_inventory_management)  
- [Routing](/Routing)  

Emma would probably say, “All these fancy equations are just ways to make the universe behave the way we want it to—until it doesn’t.”  

